05244nam a2200661Ia 9780231558969DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315589697 a10.7312/athe211542doi  a(DE-B1597)670329  a(OCoLC)1408681675  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPL747.35b.A844 2023 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.63qOCoLC223/eng/202306011 aAtherton, David C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting Violence :bThe Politics of Form in Early Modern Japanese Literature /cDavid C. Atherton. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b4 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to Readers -- tIntroduction. The Problem, Promise, and Politics of Early Modern Literary Form -- tI Creative Destruction Remaking the World in Seventeenth- Century Disaster Literature -- tII The Vengeance Variations Revenge as Form in the Fiction of Ihara Saikaku -- tIII The (Un)crucified Lovers Adultery, Punishment, and the “Truth” of Transgression -- tIV Ueda Akinari and the Form of Fiction In Which a Brother Is Celebrated for Beheading His Sister -- tV Frontier Violence Late Yomihon Form and the Bodies and Bounds of the Realm -- tEpilogue. Forms in Context, Forms Beyond Context -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEdo-period Japan was a golden age for commercial literature. A host of new narrative genres cast their gaze across the social landscape, probed the realms of history and the fantastic, and breathed new life into literary tradition. But how to understand the politics of this body of literature remains contested, in part because the defining characteristics of much early modern fiction—formulaicness, reuse of narratives, stock characters, linguistic and intertextual play, and heavy allusion to literary canon—can seem to hold social and political realities at arm’s length.David C. Atherton offers a new approach to understanding the relationship between the challenging formal features of early modern popular literature and the world beyond its pages. Focusing on depictions of violence—one of the most fraught topics for a peaceful polity ruled over by warriors—he connects concepts of form and formalization across the aesthetic and social spheres. Atherton shows how the formal features of early modern literature had the potential to alter the perception of time and space, make social and economic forces visible, defamiliarize conventions, give voice to the socially peripheral, and reshape the contours of community. Through careful readings of works by the major writers Asai Ryōi, Ihara Saikaku, Chikamatsu Monzaemon, Ueda Akinari, and Santō Kyōden, Writing Violence reveals the essential role of literary form in constructing the world—and in seeing it anew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aJapanese fictionyEdo period, 1600-1868xHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aJapanese fictionyEdo period, 1600-1868xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzJapan2DLC. 0aLiterature and society. 0aViolence in literature2DLC. 0aViolence in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook 